{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500919"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:20:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:20:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1698"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1698"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.15,0.12,0.02,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83003"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1698"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68063"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1330"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2765"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6312"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"885"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1236"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1276"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44707"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83003"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with sudden onset left-sided crushing chest pain. He has a past medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and a previous myocardial infarction two years ago. On examination, his blood pressure is 70 mmHg systolic (no diastolic reading is achieved). He is confused with cool and clammy hands and has a raised jugular venous pressure with Kussmaul\u0027s sign present. His lungs are clear to auscultation. An ECG is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Give a 250-500mL bolus of normal saline IV","Give dobutamine IV","Give morphine IV","Give furosemide IV","Give nitroglycerin (GTN) IV"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has clinical features of shock (hypotension, cool peripheries, evidence of end-organ dysfunction with confusion). His shock is most likely cardiogenic, secondary to right ventricular dysfunction, likely from an inferior myocardial infarction (the ST elevation in lead II, lead III, and lead aVF is consistent with an inferior myocardial infarction).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe most important next step in management is to achieve haemodynamic stability.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe best way to manage right ventricular failure is to maintain initial fluid support to maximise cardiac output with minimal ventricular filling pressure. Therefore, giving a 250 mL fluid bolus is appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVasopressors or inotropes are also used to maintain vital perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith very severe hypotension, norepinephrine or dopamine is used to increase inotropic and vasopressor effect (eventually causing a significant increase in afterload).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDobutamine\u003C/strong\u003E is used if the patient is not severely hypotensive as its vasodilatory effect reduces afterload and improves cardiac output (but causes a significant fall in blood pressure).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorphine\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Enitroglycerine (GTN)\u003C/strong\u003E should be avoided as his systolic blood pressure is currently less than 90 mmHg. Although these agents reduce preload, they can also cause a significant decrease in blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E is not needed currently as he has no evidence of acute pulmonary oedema (his lungs are clear). IV furosemide is important in the setting of left ventricular dysfunction, as it improves oxygenation by treating pulmonary oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAs soon as haemodynamic stability is achieved, this patient needs urgent definitive management in the form of a reperfusion intervention,\u003C/strong\u003E most likely via percutaneous coronary intervention (see the SHOCK-I and SHOCK-II cardiology trials).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnother potential cause is Dressler syndrome (pericarditis). However, the typical onset is 1-6 weeks following an acute infarction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The most important next step in management of cardiogenic shock is to achieve haemodynamic stability.","In acute inferior myocardial infarction, bradycardia and heart block can also be commonly seen on ECG."],"references":["Werdan K, Russ M, Buerke M, Prondzinsky R, Dietz S. Evidence-based Management of Cardiogenic Shock After Acute Myocardial Infarction. Interv Cardiol. 2013 Aug;8(2):73-80. doi: 10.15420/icr.2013.8.2.73. PMID: 29588754; PMCID: PMC5808586. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29588754/","Menon V, Hochman JS. Management of cardiogenic shock complicating acute myocardial infarction. Heart. 2002 Nov;88(5):531-7. doi: 10.1136/heart.88.5.531. PMID: 12381652; PMCID: PMC1767433. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12381652/","Vahdatpour C, Collins D, Goldberg S. Cardiogenic Shock. J Am Heart Assoc. 2019 Apr 16;8(8):e011991. doi: 10.1161/JAHA.119.011991. PMID: 30947630; PMCID: PMC6507212. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30947630/","Holmes, David R. Cardiogenic shock: a lethal complication of acute myocardial infarction. Reviews in cardiovascular medicine. 2019;4:131-135. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12949441/","Banning AS, Gershlick AH. Management of Multivessel Disease and Cardiogenic Shock. Interv Cardiol Clin. 2016 Oct;5(4):533-540. doi: 10.1016/j.iccl.2016.06.009. Epub 2016 Aug 13. PMID: 28582001. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28582001/","Shah AH, Puri R, Kalra A. Management of cardiogenic shock complicating acute myocardial infarction: A review. Clin Cardiol. 2019 Apr;42(4):484-493. doi: 10.1002/clc.23168. Epub 2019 Mar 27. PMID: 30815887; PMCID: PMC6712338. Avaiable from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30815887/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68063"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1698"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17974"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17974"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eccb0700-b0a4-4868-9563-0ce2dbb973ed.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/eccb0700-b0a4-4868-9563-0ce2dbb973ed.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":353}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic